                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"><span style="font-style: italic">This from stupid people, ones that I doubt are 'controlling' the market because those items are NEVER SOLD.</span>
<br />

<br />
See, that's where you are wrong.  What you have to realize is that in a Bazaar economy, everything eventually sells.  
<br />

<br />
Here's an absurd example that happens to be true.
<br />

<br />
The price of essense emeralds on the Rathe is 300 plats.  You can buy them for that any day.  There is one guy out there selling them for 5000 plats.  He does sell them, because people don't know, or don't have time to find another seller.
<br />

<br />
Now if he could control of the supply of essense emeralds, he could sell them for 10000 platinum.  This guy isn't playing that game, but he could by simply by buying every essense emerald that anyone else sells.
<br />

<br />
I've seen people do this with Ornate molds.  It works, because the short-term supply is constrained.
<br />

<br />
Now, I don't buy the 'Grand Unified Conspiracy' theory about ruining the economy.  I think that the IGE/Yantis merger is just a matter of someone's ego running rampant.
<br />

<br />
Still, this post holds a core of truth.  That truth is that platinum is becoming hugely concentrated in a few hands, and this concentration is fueling the platinum sales business.  The problem is exacerbated by Elemental and Time enabled guilds needing no platinum in game.  All thier gear is nodrop and they can generate immense fortunes by selling elemental items to the 80% of the game who is not elemental enabled.
<br />

<br />
Concentrated platinum is bad for the little guy who is out there killing kobolds.  It raised his prices, and it makes the millioniares much less interested in selling nickel and dime items.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
